CommonFields.Title: The Mechanical Properties of Epoxy Composites Filled with Rubbery Copolymer Grafted SiO2
Author: Gao, Jianing
Li, Junting
Benicewicz, Brian C.
Zhao, Su
Hillborg, Henrik
Schadler, Linda S.
CommonFields.Location: Department of Materials Science & Engineering, Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, 110 8th Street, Troy, NY 12180, USA

Mixing.Description:
The CTA-anchored nanoparticles, monomer (HMA or GMA),
            AIBN and THF were added to a dried Schlenk tube. The mixture was
            degassed by three freeze-pump-thaw cycles, backfilled with
            nitrogen, and then placed in an oil bath at 60°C for various
            intervals.
Mixing.Mixer: dried Schlenk tube in oil bath

Cooling.Description:
The polymerization was quenched in ice
            water.

Mixing.Description:
The methylene chloride solution was mixed with epoxy
          resin.

Drying-Evaporation.Description:
The solvent in the mixture was evaporated until the
          mass of the mixture remained unchanged, indicating that all the
          solvent was gone.

Mixing.Description:
The hardener and the catalyst were then added to the
          particle-resin mixture and thoroughly mixed using a Hauschild Dual
          Asymmetric Centrifugal mixer.

MoldingInfo.Description:
The mixture was cured at 80 °C for 10 hours and 135
            °C for 10 h in a silicone mold.

Transmission_Electron_Microscopy.Description:
The sub surface failure was characterized by a JOEL CM12
      transmitted electron microscope (TEM) on the vertical plane beneath the
      fracture surface.

Scanning_Electron_Microscopy.Description:
The fracture surface of the neat epoxy and nanocomposites
      was analyzed by a JEOL 6330F field emission scanning electron
      microscope.

Dynamic_Mechanical_Analysis.Description:
The glass transition temperatures of the nanocomposites
      were measured by dynamic mechanical analysis on a DMTA V from Rheometric
      Scientific from −150 to 200°C at 2°C/min.

Differential_Scanning_Calorimetry.Description:
The curing process of the epoxy matrix was studied by an
      isoconversional method on a Modulated Differential Scanning Calorimeter
      (MDSC) model Q100 from TA Instruments. About 10 mg uncured sample wax
      cured in closed aluminum pans in the MDSC at heating rates of 2.5, 5,
      7.5, 10 and 12.5°C/min. The glass transition temperatures of the
      nanocomposites were also measured by DSC at a heating rate of
      10°C/min.

ImageFile.Description:
"A": mirror zone, "B": mist zone and "C": hackle
      zone.
